# Get top-rated 5 restaurants in 2 km with similar menu items.
# check the overlap count in the output, that is used 
# to measure the similarity between the menu items of Village Soul of India and other nearby restaurants.

nearby_restaurants = pd.DataFrame({
    "Restaurant": [
        "Broadway Diner", "Calda Pizzeria", "Sakana", "Great Wok", "Tikka Charcoal Grill",
        "La Candela", "Greek Xpress", "Lemonleaf Grill", "Hicksville Diner", "Spice Symphony"
    ],
    "Distance (km)": [1.5, 1.8, 1.2, 1.7, 2.0, 2.2, 1.9, 2.5, 2.8, 3.0],
    "Rating": [4.0, 4.5, 4.3, 4.2, 4.7, 4.1, 3.8, 4.2, 4.0, 4.6],
    "Menu Items": [
        ["Butter Chicken", "Naan", "Soup"],
        ["Pizza", "Biryani", "Naan"],
        ["Butter Chicken", "Biryani", "Sushi"],
        ["Soup", "Spring Rolls", "Fried Rice"],
        ["Butter Chicken", "Naan", "Biryani"],
        ["Ceviche", "Biryani", "Rice"],
        ["Gyro", "Naan", "Salad"],
        ["Thai Curry", "Spring Rolls", "Naan"],
        ["Butter Chicken", "Biryani", "Naan"],
        ["Paneer Tikka", "Butter Chicken", "Chaat"]
    ]
})

village_menu = {"Butter Chicken", "Naan", "Biryani", "Paneer Tikka", "Chaat"}

nearby_restaurants["Overlap Count"] = nearby_restaurants["Menu Items"].apply(
    lambda items: len(village_menu.intersection(items))
)

top_restaurants = nearby_restaurants[nearby_restaurants["Distance (km)"] <= 2].sort_values(
    by=["Overlap Count", "Rating"], ascending=[False, False]
)

print("Top-Rated Restaurants within 3 km with Similar Menu Items:")
print(top_restaurants[["Restaurant", "Distance (km)", "Rating", "Overlap Count"]].to_string(index=False))

# DISPLAY menu items & prices for Village + each restaurant

village_menu = pd.DataFrame({
    "Menu Item": ["Butter Chicken", "Naan", "Biryani", "Paneer Tikka", "Chaat"],
    "Village Price ($)": [12.99, 2.99, 14.99, 10.99, 6.99]
})

restaurant_menus = {
    "Broadway Diner": {"Butter Chicken": 13.50, "Naan": 3.50, "Soup": 5.99},
    "Calda Pizzeria": {"Pizza": 9.99, "Biryani": 14.80, "Naan": 3.20},
    "Sakana": {"Butter Chicken": 14.00, "Biryani": 15.50, "Sushi": 10.99},
    "Great Wok": {"Soup": 4.99, "Spring Rolls": 5.50, "Fried Rice": 8.99},
    "Tikka Charcoal Grill": {"Butter Chicken": 12.75, "Naan": 2.95, "Biryani": 14.95}
}

menu_comparison = village_menu.copy()
for restaurant, menu_items in restaurant_menus.items():
    menu_comparison[restaurant] = menu_comparison["Menu Item"].apply(
        lambda item: menu_items.get(item, "N/A")
    )
print("Menu Items and Prices Comparison:")
print("\n")
print(menu_comparison.to_string(index=False))

# Village busy times 

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

# manually scraped data
busy_times_data = {
    "Day": ["Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday"],
    "6 AM": [5, 5, 5, 5, 5, 5, 10],
    "9 AM": [10, 5, 5, 5, 10, 20, 30],
    "12 PM": [30, 20, 10, 20, 40, 70, 90],
    "3 PM": [50, 40, 20, 40, 60, 90, 110],
    "6 PM": [80, 70, 50, 60, 90, 120, 110],
    "9 PM": [100, 90, 80, 90, 110, 150, 140],
    "12 AM": [40, 30, 20, 30, 40, 60, 50]
}

# Convert to DataFrame
busy_times_df = pd.DataFrame(busy_times_data)

# Calculate average busyness
busy_times_df["Average Busyness"] = busy_times_df.iloc[:, 1:].mean(axis=1)

# Define busy days
threshold = 70
busy_days = busy_times_df[busy_times_df["Average Busyness"] > threshold]["Day"]

# Plot the graph
time_intervals = ["6 AM", "9 AM", "12 PM", "3 PM", "6 PM", "9 PM", "12 AM"]
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

for i, row in busy_times_df.iterrows():
    if row["Day"] in busy_days.values:
        plt.plot(time_intervals, row[1:8], label=row["Day"], marker='o', linewidth=2.5, color="red")
    else:
        plt.plot(time_intervals, row[1:8], label=row["Day"], marker='o', linestyle='dotted')

plt.title("Village Busy Times (Highlighted Busy Days)", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Time Intervals", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Busyness Level", fontsize=12)
plt.legend(title="Days", loc="upper left", fontsize=10)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

import pandas as pd

# temperature and rain data (manually scraped)
weather_data = {
    "Month": ["January", "February", "March", "April", "May", "June", "July", "August", "September", "October", "November", "December"],
    "High Temp (F)": [38, 39, 49, 60, 70, 79, 85, 83, 76, 64, 53, 45],
    "Low Temp (F)": [25, 24, 33, 42, 52, 61, 68, 66, 59, 49, 39, 32],
    "Rainfall (in)": [2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5, 3, 3, 2, 4],
    "Snowfall (in)": [9, 11, 5, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 4],
}

weather_df = pd.DataFrame(weather_data)
print(weather_df)

# Plot High and Low Temperature
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
plt.plot(weather_data["Month"], weather_data["High Temp (F)"], label="High Temp (F)", color="red", marker='o', linewidth=2)
plt.plot(weather_data["Month"], weather_data["Low Temp (F)"], label="Low Temp (F)", color="blue", marker='o', linewidth=2)

# Add labels and annotations
for i, temp in enumerate(weather_data["High Temp (F)"]):
    plt.text(i, temp + 1, f"{temp}", color="red", ha='center', fontsize=10)
for i, temp in enumerate(weather_data["Low Temp (F)"]):
    plt.text(i, temp - 3, f"{temp}", color="blue", ha='center', fontsize=10)

plt.title("Monthly Temperature Trends in Hicksville", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel("Month", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Temperature (F)", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(fontsize=12)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Plot Rainfall and Snowfall
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
bar_width = 0.35
months = range(len(weather_data["Month"]))
plt.bar(months, weather_data["Rainfall (in)"], label="Rainfall (in)", color="blue", alpha=0.7, width=bar_width, align='center')
plt.bar(months, weather_data["Snowfall (in)"], label="Snowfall (in)", color="gray", alpha=0.7, width=bar_width, align='edge')

# Add labels to bars
for i, value in enumerate(weather_data["Rainfall (in)"]):
    plt.text(i - 0.1, value + 0.2, f"{value}\"", color="blue", ha='center', fontsize=10)
for i, value in enumerate(weather_data["Snowfall (in)"]):
    if value > 0:
        plt.text(i + 0.2, value + 0.2, f"{value}\"", color="gray", ha='center', fontsize=10)

plt.title("Monthly Precipitation Trends in Hicksville", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel("Month", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Precipitation (inches)", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(months, weather_data["Month"], fontsize=12, rotation=45)
plt.yticks(fontsize=12)
plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True, linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# DISPLAY Village menu with predicted prices

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

# Weather data (manually scraped)
weather_data = {
    "Month": ["January", "February", "March", "April", "May", "June", "July", "August", "September", "October", "November", "December"],
    "High Temp (F)": [38, 39, 49, 60, 70, 79, 85, 83, 76, 64, 53, 45],
    "Low Temp (F)": [25, 24, 33, 42, 52, 61, 68, 66, 59, 49, 39, 32],
    "Rainfall (in)": [2, 2, 3, 3, 3, 4, 4, 5, 3, 3, 2, 4],
    "Snowfall (in)": [9, 11, 5, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 4],
}
weather_df = pd.DataFrame(weather_data)

# Menu data
village_menu = pd.DataFrame({
    "Menu Item": ["Butter Chicken", "Naan", "Biryani", "Paneer Tikka", "Chaat"],
    "Base Price ($)": [12.99, 2.99, 14.99, 10.99, 6.99]
})

# Training data
training_data = pd.DataFrame({
    "Temperature (F)": [30, 40, 50, 70, 80],
    "Precipitation (in)": [1, 1, 0, 0, 0],
    "Busyness": [3, 2, 1, 1, 1],
    "Price Multiplier": [1.2, 1.1, 1.0, 1.0, 1.0],
})

# Train the model
X_train = training_data[["Temperature (F)", "Precipitation (in)", "Busyness"]]
y_train = training_data["Price Multiplier"]
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Current conditions (example: replace with real data)
temp = 43
precip = 3
busyness = 3
current_conditions = pd.DataFrame([[temp, precip, busyness]], columns=["Temperature (F)", "Precipitation (in)", "Busyness"])
predicted_multiplier = model.predict(current_conditions)[0]

# Update menu prices
village_menu["Predicted Price ($)"] = village_menu["Base Price ($)"] * predicted_multiplier

# Check conditions
temp_condition = temp < 45
rain_condition = precip > 2
busyness_condition = busyness > 2

if temp_condition and rain_condition and busyness_condition:
    print("Conditions met: Prices increased.")
else:
    print("Conditions not met: Prices remain the same.")


print("\nWeather Data:")
print(weather_df)
print("\nUpdated Menu Prices:")
print(village_menu)
